SIMPLE: plebeian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plebeian
<hw>Ple*be"ian</hw> <pr>(pl⟦esl⟧*b⟦emac⟧"y⟦ait⟧n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>plebeius</ets>, from <ets>plebs</ets>, <ets>plebis</ets>,
the common people: cf. F. <ets>pl⟦eacute⟧b⟦eacute⟧ien</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the Roman <xex>plebs</xex>, or
common people.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the common people; vulgar;
common; <as>as, <ex>plebeian</ex> sports; a <ex>plebeian</ex>
throng.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plebeian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plebeian
<hw>Ple*be"ian</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the
<membof>plebs</membof>, or common people of ancient Rome, in distinction
from <contr>patrician</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of the common people, or lower rank of
men.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plebeiance</ent>⟦br⟧
